Solid Priorities for Fragile States
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared by the fallout of the COVID-19 pandemic.
However, the world's most "fragile" states face a particularly complex set of issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and inadequate public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
<p>Ce dont chaque pays a besoin afin de traverser la pandémie est précisément ce qu’il manque aux États fragiles : un appareil d’État en mesure d’élaborer et de mettre en œuvre un plan d’action, un corps de police efficace pour faire appliquer les règles, des programmes sociaux qui fournissent des fonds, de l’approvisionnement ainsi que des services de santé pour soigner les personnes infectées.</p>
Le manque de moyens de l’État se fait immédiatement sentir dans le domaine de la santé publique.
Alors que l’Europe compte 4 000 lits aux soins intensifs par million d’habitants, plusieurs régions d’Afrique n’en ont que cinq par million d’habitants.
Le Mali possède seulement trois ventilateurs pour l’ensemble du pays.
Une riposte efficace passe également par la confiance dans l’intervention de l’État.
<p>LONDON/MONROVI/LIGALE – However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not enjoy much popular support.</p>
In countries emerging from conflict or plagued by endemic corruption, many people will hesitate to back a government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to assist those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not sufficient to meet these needs.
<p>Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to their youthful demographic weight and geographic remoteness.</p>
However, as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, we must acknowledge that this did not happen.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries hit hardest by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will likely be more severe for fragile states. These effects will not only result from national lockdowns but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has faltered, remittances from expatriates have dropped, basic commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
<p>Puisque les États fragiles comptent sur les importations pour la majeure partie de leur alimentation, on parle de plus en plus de « faim » et même de « famine ».</p>
<p>Nous devrions à présent avoir compris que les problèmes des pays moins nantis deviennent pour la plupart des problèmes mondiaux que ce soit sous la forme de migrations massives, d’organisations criminelles ou terroristes, ou de répercussions économiques.</p>
<p>Étant donné que la moitié des populations démunies vivra dans des États fragiles d’ici 2030, ces problèmes ne cesseront de s’aggraver.</p>
<p>C’est pourquoi le Council on State Fragility s’est fixé comme priorité absolue d’attirer l’attention sur les défis spécifiques que ces pays doivent relever.</p>
<p>Le conseil, composé d’anciens dirigeants mondiaux, de ministres, de diplomates, de personnalités du monde des affaires, d’universitaires ainsi que de présidents d’organismes de développement, alliera des recherches de pointe à de méticules connaissances politiques. Il aura comme but d’orienter les décideurs politiques nationaux et internationaux qui régiront comment les États fragiles se sortiront de cette crise et qui s’attelleront à leurs problèmes plus vastes et profonds.</p>
<p>Decentralization, adaptability, and smart use of data will be essential.</p>
<p>For example, it is widely proven that targeted 'lockdowns' of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.</p>
<p>Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.</p>
<p>However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades.</p>
<p>We propose five recommendations.</p>
Premièrement, l'accès à la protection sociale doit être plus simple et plus rapide.
Parfois, cela sera synonyme d'une admissibilité universelle plutôt qu'un ciblage précis.
Les réseaux téléphoniques mobiles devraient être mis à profit afin de recueillir des renseignements sur les besoins immédiats et de verser de petites prestations régulières (bien que d'une durée limitée).
Deuxièmement, la production alimentaire nationale devrait être encouragée.
Par exemple, la Sierra Leone, qui cultivait du riz, est devenue de plus en plus dépendante lors des dernières décennies.
<p>Generally speaking, Africa has 60% of the world's unused arable land.</p>
<p>Local initiatives to produce staple crops should be rapidly scaled up.</p>
<p>Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier nations.</p>
<p>When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe until all are safe.</p>
<p>We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to guarantee rapid and widespread distribution.</p>
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small enterprises in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffer the harmful consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in larger projects in more significant economies).
Yet, precisely these small enterprises need more substantial investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is estimated that countries receiving bilateral development aid will owe about 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
<p>To prevent this financial shock, we urge all members of the G20 to suspend accumulated debts for a time not only until next year, but until the end of the crisis.</p>
<p>In addition, it is essential that all fragile states obtain emergency funding to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions—especially countries that do not typically have access to funding from the World Bank or International Monetary Fund.</p>
<p>COVID-19 will worsen existing problems in all fragile states around the world.</p>
<p>However, if the international community responds promptly, we can mitigate the worst impacts of the pandemic.</p>
<p>If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.</p>
